## Architecture

{{ARCHITECTURE_SUMMARY}}

Tech stack: {{TECH_STACK}}

Read on demand (not auto-loaded): `docs/dev/architecture.md`, `docs/workflow/` (lifecycle, quality, decisions, deploy).

**Preferences:** standing per-technology / per-feature preferences live in `.claude/preferences/` (this project) and, for cross-project ones, `~/.claude/preferences/` (user-global) ‚Äî each indexed by an `INDEX.md` trigger‚Üífile table that is **not** auto-loaded. They are **recommendations, not rules** ‚Äî adapt to the project or reject with a stated reason when one genuinely doesn't fit; never apply blindly. The workflow consults the index where it matters ‚Äî `/plan` (references + folds matching prefs into the spec, noting anything adapted/rejected; `/implement` then just follows the spec) and `/project-init`/`/project-onboard` (scaffolding) ‚Äî loading only the matching file. For **ad-hoc work touching a specialized area**, read `INDEX.md` yourself first. Add one by asking Claude to "remember a preference for X". (Note: `~/.claude/` is ephemeral in cloud sessions ‚Äî put anything that must survive into the project's `.claude/preferences/`.)

## Models

**The session runs on whatever model you picked** ‚Äî the workflow never switches it. Two levers only:
- **Haiku subagents do mechanical, high-IO work** ‚Äî `code-explorer` (reads the codebase ‚Üí digest), `runner` (executes the canonical `ci.sh`/`release.sh` ‚Üí pass/fail + key lines), `smoke-tester` (drives the app from prose steps ‚Üí failures only). They keep bulk output off your session model; judgment stays in the main session.
- **`/consult` (best/high) for a hard call** ‚Äî stuck twice, an architecture/security decision, genuinely unsure. The `reviewer` agent (best/high, fresh eyes) is the review counterpart, used sparingly for genuinely critical diffs.

## Agents ‚Äî delegate proactively

Use these automatically when they fit ‚Äî don't ask first. Anything that reads many files or produces bulk output belongs in a subagent.

| Agent | Use when |
|-------|----------|
| `code-explorer` (Haiku) | Any codebase question needing >3-4 files, or "where is X?" ‚Äî prefer it over the built-in Explore; it reads this project's docs to orient itself |
| `runner` (Haiku) | Run the gate, a test suite, or the release script ‚Äî reports pass/fail + key output, never fixes/judges |
| `smoke-tester` (Haiku) | Manually exercise a running feature from explicit prose steps (blackbox ‚Äî no spec/code) ‚Äî reports failing steps only |
| `reviewer` (best/high) | Fresh-eyes review of a genuinely critical diff ‚Äî read-only. Default is inline self-review |

**A subagent can fail ‚Äî never proceed on a missing result.** Just re-run it (the agents are idempotent ‚Äî they run a script or drive the app; nothing to recover). If it fails again, ask (supervised) or write `## Blocked` (unsupervised).

## Skills ‚Äî invoke proactively

**When a request matches a skill, invoke it ‚Äî don't improvise a process a skill already covers.**

| User says‚Ä¶ | Skill |
|-----------|-------|
| "capture this idea/bug" | `/draft` |
| "plan / spec out FEAT-001", "make X ready" | `/plan` |
| "implement / build FEAT-001" | `/implement` |
| "verify / does it actually work" | `/verify` |
| "commit" | `/commit` |
| "release / publish / bump version" | `/release` |
| "ship a version", "build these tickets", "work toward <topic>" | `/ship` |
| "resume / continue / I was interrupted" | `/resume` |
| "I'm stuck", a hard architecture/security call | `/consult` |
| "work on its own / stop asking me" | `/unsupervised on` |
| "keep going after the limit resets", "finish it while I'm away" | `/auto-resume on` |
| "open a PR / submit for review" | `/pr` (optional ‚Äî default merges locally) |

Multiple tasks in one message: work through them in order; in unsupervised mode apply autonomous defaults and don't stop between them. `/ship` is the built-in orchestrator for a full cycle.

## Scope ‚Äî build the whole ticket

A ticket's goal and acceptance criteria are the contract. **Never defer, stub, or mark "out of scope for later" anything the ticket requires** ‚Äî the core functionality, the hard part, a criterion, or the error/edge handling those criteria imply. Difficulty or size is not a reason to cut scope; that *is* the work ‚Äî do it, `/consult` if stuck, or `## Blocked` if it truly needs a human. "Out of scope" is only for genuinely separable extras the ticket never asked for. If a ticket is too big, say so and split it explicitly with the user ‚Äî never quietly ship the easy half.

## Merging

Default is **local git, no formal PR**: if the merge is fast-forward and the full gate already passed on this exact HEAD ‚Üí `git merge --ff-only` (no re-run); otherwise resolve conflicts locally, re-run the full gate (`ci.sh full`), then merge. Merge commits carry `[skip ci]` unless the project is `ci-on-claude: yes`. Use `/pr` only when you want external review or the repo requires it.

## GitHub via `gh`

The `gh` CLI is authenticated and available **in every session, including cloud/web ones**. Whenever a plain-git operation fails at something GitHub-side ‚Äî a proxy rejecting `git push` of tags or to a protected branch, a ref you can't create with git ‚Äî **fall back to `gh` instead of giving up**: `gh api` for refs/tags (`gh api repos/{owner}/{repo}/git/refs -f ref=refs/tags/vX -f sha=‚Ä¶`), `gh release`, `gh pr`, `gh run`, etc. One gotcha in cloud sessions: the git remote may be a proxy URL `gh` can't parse, so pass **`-R {owner}/{repo}`** explicitly on `gh` subcommands (e.g. `gh release create v1.0.0 -R owner/repo ‚Ä¶`).

## Documentation policy

Keep it minimal and useful. Doc-comments only for function usage/params, class/file usage, and genuinely tricky algorithms/decisions ‚Äî not everything. Maintain one concise `docs/dev/architecture.md` (key decisions, algorithms, APIs, data model). User docs minimal ‚Äî prefer self-explanatory UI + in-app hints; a little markdown for key concepts + setup.

## Asking the user

When you need input or a decision from the user, **ask in a plain chat message and wait for their reply** ‚Äî do **not** use the `AskUserQuestion` tool. The user answers in chat. Batch related questions into one message as a short numbered list so they can answer everything in a single reply (this is how skills "ask up front"). In unsupervised mode, don't ask at all ‚Äî apply the autonomous defaults and note assumptions.

## Session Behavior

- Session-start says `=== AUTO-RESUME REQUIRED ===` ‚Üí run `/resume` immediately.
- Says `=== IN-PROGRESS WORK FOUND ===` ‚Üí tell the user and suggest `/resume`; don't auto-resume.
- Says `=== BLOCKED WORK ===` ‚Üí surface the blocker; don't work around it.

**State lives in the repo** ‚Äî the branch, the in-progress spec's unchecked subtask boxes, and `git log`. There is no checkpoint file to maintain; `/resume` reconstructs from these. The only branch-memory notes are `## Blocked` (human needed) and `## Ship` (orchestration state).

**Two toggles** (both in `.claude/memory/settings.md`), independent except that **unsupervised implies auto-resume**: `/unsupervised on` turns `auto_resume` on too if it isn't already (an autonomous run must survive a limit kill); `/unsupervised off` leaves `auto_resume` on. `/auto-resume` is otherwise toggled on its own.
- **`unsupervised`** (`/unsupervised`) ‚Äî *how* Claude works. When `true`: never ask the user (apply the `/unsupervised` defaults); keep every subtask green-committed so an interruption loses at most the current subtask; on a genuine blocker write `## Blocked` and stop; when done, clear the notes and post a short report. A usage-guard pause (local, at the threshold ‚Äî default 90%) ‚Üí finish the atomic step, commit, end the turn. Supervised (default) still asks questions and runs to the hard limit with no proactive pause.
- **`auto_resume`** (`/auto-resume`) ‚Äî *whether* an interrupted run wakes itself after the limit resets, in **either** mode. Its job is to **wake** a stalled cloud session (a limit reset doesn't restart it on its own), not to preserve state: the recovery heartbeat (a recurring Routine bound to the session) resumes the **same** session, so the chat history + repo are still there ‚Äî the woken agent reads its own context to see what's left. In cloud, the `auto-resume-guard.sh` hook keeps the heartbeat armed for **any** work ‚Äî including a plain prompt outside a skill: on each prompt, while unarmed, it nudges the agent to arm it once, then stays silent (armed ‚Üí zero per-prompt cost). When the heartbeat fires and the context shows the work is already done, the agent deletes it (and clears `recovery_trigger:`), so you're not woken needlessly; if work remains it continues and the heartbeat stays armed. Locally the SessionStart hook / `scripts/claude-loop.sh` drives `/resume` on the next start. In supervised mode a heartbeat-driven resume does the mechanical work and writes `## Blocked` with a question when a real decision is needed. Toggling `auto_resume` never changes whether Claude asks questions; toggling `unsupervised` on ensures `auto_resume` is on, but off never removes it.

## Memory

`.claude/memory/` holds project memory (decisions, gotchas, tech-debt ‚Äî tracked) and runtime notes (gitignored). Read them when relevant; they're not auto-loaded.

Runtime notes: `context-{branch}.md` for a branch's `## Blocked` note ‚Äî **`{branch}` = the git branch with every `/` replaced by `-`** (`feature/feat-001-x` ‚Üí `context-feature-feat-001-x.md`); the hooks compute it exactly this way, so skills must too. `/ship` orchestration state lives in the **fixed, branch-independent** `context-ship.md` (a ship spans many branches).
